rawReviews.text:
So a few years ago, we called them out to inspect our septic system before we bought our home.  We were given a clean bill of health and told we were good to go, they pumped it, and we moved on.  Couldn't tell whose name was on the inspection report, initials look like M.H.

Fast-forward to present day, our pump is not running.  I make the call to them and they send a tech out (they responded very quickly and the tech that came out, Joey, was informative and helpful).  He told us that the pump was not plugged into the float switch correctly and because of this, the motor had burned up.  This was not mentioned on our buyer's inspection before we purchased the house.  I went ahead and had them replace the pump (which was quite expensive).  When asked if they could do anything on their price because their original inspection failed to identify what seemed like a pretty easy catch, they were pretty accusatory as if we were trying to dodge paying our bill.  They asked questions about whether landscapers (we don't have any) or anyone else would have changed the way the plug was plugged in (definitely did not happen).  Shame on me for not doing my research and making sure the plug was installed correctly when we bought the house, but I feel that they should have caught this and obviously they felt as if they would have if it had been that way when they made their initial inspection.  They have a good reputation with others in the neighborhood so I would probably give them another chance but I remain pretty unhappy with the miss on the initial inspection.  As far as the install today went, I guess time will tell.  The outdoor outlet that the pump is plugged into was left zip-tied closed and seems like it is smashing the pump plug/wire.  Hopefully this doesn't cause more issues down the road.

Later on, when implementing a new rear lawn with irrigation, I hired them to install a backflow for the irrigation. After that I had a leak in the master bath shower where they unearthed a messy plumbing job from the flip. It cost me a fortune to get this fixed (I don't mean over priced, instead them cleaning up someone else's botched work), but Bryan and his dad did a great job and I know there won't be a repeat issue in this area. Later on (yet again) I found a spigot on the front of the house wasn't working and they repaired for a very good price. Then late last night after returning home from Christmas festivities, I discovered a pipe had burst from the cold, so I texted Bryan hoping he may have time to assess the problem. Not only did he exchange texts with me around midnight Christmas night, but had 2 guys out here by 11am and they were able to cap off the leak to an outside spigot, plus solve a mystery about no gas coming in to a gas fireplace.

rawReviews.text: I currently has these guys come out in august to my home. I had something stopping up my pipes but I wasn’t sure what it was and didn’t have the correct tools. Therefore, they took the snake and went down the toilet then couldn’t find where it was stopped up at then dug a hole in my outside pipe going to the sewage. They then discovered that a root was the issue and old pipes. To shorten the story…the guys basically had to cut a piece of my pipe off to get the snake in and told me they would cap it back off. As you can see in the pictures this was not done. Not sure how much dirt has went into my septic tank since then but a terrible job as far as being trustworthy and honest with me. I paid for your full work which was not achieved.
rawReviews.responseFromOwnerText:
I’m so sorry you felt the need write a negative review. The procedure to access thru the pipe is what plumbers call a “hot patch.” In plumbing there is a process of elimination. We obviously want to access thru the toilet first if you don’t have a clean out. The only reason to have to access the pipe outside is if the fittings are on a tee instead of a sweep bend. Which is illegal now days to plumb tees in. Since I hat was the case with your pipes. The next step would have been to access pipe outside or install a clean out. Once we access the clean out or cut hole in pipe we can then jet or snake line. We did unclog the line. We take pride in what we do and if you would have called the office we could have explain this process so you would have know we were professional. 256-454-5962 is our office number. We would love to talk to you.

Also I remember this very well you sat out and watched us the whole and you  were nice. You saw the issues we ran into considering you just bought a house and we’re finding out it had a lot of issues. We left it open because you were suppose to let us come back and replace the section of pipe and install a clean out. We were completely honest and transparent. You made this review sound like we were dishonest. That’s unfortunate because you and I know that’s not true.

Thanks
Nick Preston
